The active ingredient in the juice[@ if either of you can think of a funny or appropriate drug name, feel free to add it. Although the later portions of this passage suggest that the juice's properties are not mediated through solely pharmeceutical means. ~C] was highly unstable, which had always struck Martinius as appropriate, both thematically and in game-balance terms. It could be acquired, but not hoarded. Planned for, but not relied on. He twisted his wedding ring around his ring finger, an unconscious prayer wheel churning out one continuous litany.

Into the kitchen. Tremors increasing, the last swallows-worth of juice swirling around the sides of the glass. He licked his lips. Dry. Pass by the to-do list lying disregarded on the granite counter; keep disregarding. "We had a good thing going for a while, didn't we?" Out of the kitchen.

For a moment, he stopped by the window by the door in the entranceway vestibule, his bare toes butting up against the chill rubber of one of innumerable pairs of boots which overflowed the boot-rack. He watched the petals of snow drift down. Each unique, proverbially. Irreplaceable in transit. And upon arrival, a homogenous component of the homogenous bulk of the snow. A metaphor for death, or birth? Either. Both. It's just snow. So beautiful. So...unfortunate. They'd always toyed with the idea of living on the islands, with their crowd-controlled weather. They'd never have done it. Neither had felt that control on that scale was good for a man.

The snowfall had delayed, for nearly two weeks now, the juice delivery. Miss *née* Gloria Undine had gone to try to meet it in the city, to bring it back with their own methods, better adapted to the weather.

He poured himself a shuddering glass of water and it played a merry jingle against his teeth. The water was dry. So dry. His skin was dry, the air was dry, the letters in his mailbox were dry, the whole globe of the earth was almost crackling, and the finger of juice remaining—he looked at it askance—was dry beyond endurance, beyond reason. Wet's opposite.[$ Moisn't]

He glanced at the door. Imagined how the hinges would creak in the soft way they did, letting one of them know that the other was home at last.

A squeak: his bare heel against the hardwood as he about-faced sharply, backtracking into the kitchen. A liquid ringing: a long knife withdrawn from the knife-block. A pause. A creak (not the door, but a cabinet). A clink. Further clinks, a lolloping gurgle, a vigorous sloshing. A pop: the top of a jar of beautifully brined olives being opened. If he was feeling dry anyway...

He needed something wet. He *needed* it. He couldn't see another way, now.

