The warm water of the bath was getting nicely wet. That was one thing Mr. Kijller had held out for: a bath he could stretch out in. It had been a bit inconvenient to fit into the bathroom situation, but they'd both become glad of it, for various reasons. Now one more.

It was still, and his ears picked up the approaching hum of an engine. He let himself sink a little further into the tub. The stinging along his wrists was fading.[@ I also did 0 research into what suicide-via-wrist slitting actually entails/feels like, because I did not want to. ~C]

The last of the juice's efficacy winked at him as it swirled down his body's drain. He felt the weakness of his extremities and knew he had chosen the right path.

From outside: "Oh honey, I asked you to clear the ice off the steps! Anyway, I got the—" And then a squawk. Not a scream, nothing dramatic. The squawk of a mildly surprised bird.

He listened. He erupted from the tub, wet and water streaming off him, raw twanging hollow strength filling his limbs, replacing their vanished vigor. His foot slipped from under him and he caromed off the wall without noticing on his angular, straight-line, no-allotment-for-curves path to the front door.

She had broken her neck—*he* had broken her neck—and slid off side of the steps to the ground. She looked like an image badly superimposed on a stock background. This could not be real. Not *this* death.[@ Another thing—how fast *does* someone die when they break their neck? People talk about like it's instant, but is that just due to the neck-down paralysis? Would her eyes find his? ~C]

He fell down the steps, against without much interest, and scrambled around to her on his hands and knees, staring. He turned his face away and vomited up the juice and the water and the cocktail and the beer and the bile.

She lay like a damaged bird, and like a damaged bird he held her, gently as though there were any more damage to be avoided. She was still warm from life, he from the bath, and their temperatures dropped together like eagles clasping talons in a mating-dive. Dropping with his tears, and the blood from her mouth.

"It was nice while it lasted, ol' Bess," he whispered. He looked into their house, the scene of his flitting, then at the car, at the boxes of juice scattered about the steps, at the steps themselves. And he through back his head and his rooms and grounds echoed for the last time with helplessly maniacal laughter.

