"—and initialization is complete. Starting program," concluded the Third Voice.

"*Surrēxit*," intoned the Second Voice.

"Martinius Kijller," said the First Voice.

The Voices aren't indescribable. But they are nondescript, because they aren't being described, *pro tem*.

Martinius opened his eyes. He found, to his mild surprise, that he was not restrained, nor was he lying on a slab, or an operating table, or anything of the sort. He was in a cushy recliner, the sort that would indeed be difficult to get out of, but not in an 'extreme security threat, terminate at least sign of non-compliance' way.

He raised his hand and examined his inner wrist in the not-light of the active, but blank, terminal before him.

More briefly, he examined his fury at his continued existence, cold and implacable and storm-riven as the surface of the Arctic sea. And below that, vast as the waters below that surface, the abyss of his grief.

"So. Is this cybernetics, or run-of-the-mill necromancy?" he asked.[$ At this point, the question of whether this is flippancy on Martinius' part or if necromancy is indeed routinely practiced in this age should remain a tactfully inconsistent blur in the reader's mind.]

"Ah, Mr. Kijller. I knew you would be an admirable selection," said the First Voice fondly.

"Both," answered the Second.

"Neither," responded the Third.

"How much do you know about the principles by which the Flying Islands are suspended, in defiance of the natural order[@ The Big Natural, as it is called. ~C]?" First again.

Martinius hadn't been making noise; nevertheless, at this, he grew quiet. After several moments, he licked his lips. "I see. You are aware that I am going to kill you, whoever[@ I think this is correct and it shouldn't be 'whomever', but I'm not certain. ~C] you are?"

"Naturally."

"As you should."

"We're counting on it."

"Then why bring me back?" Even as he spoke, some text, limned in green light, appeared on the black screen.

"Read the presented text," said Third. "Only comprehension of the discrete tokens is necessary; holistic comprehension is not required, would be counterproductive, and is formally impossible."

"After having done so," said Second, "if you turn your question inward, you shall find it answered, and along with it many others also, truth radiating from this central point in a glorious epiphany."

Brief pause while his eyes saccaded across the screen. "...what the hell?" he asked. And then it was true.

By and large. He still had a couple of questions.

"Why...this?" He gestured at the file and its filename with a mixture of amusement and mild disgust.

The First Voice said, "We find that in order for the process to succeed, a number of factors you might not have to expect have to be...*right*."[$ If this were a televised program, this would be the moment that Thomas Metcalf's leitmotif would briefly swell.]

"Why...now?"

"Because at this moment—"

